{
  "What is a non-inertial reference frame?": "",
  "Any frame on Earth": "",
  "A frame moving at constant velocity": "",
  "A reference frame that is accelerating or rotating": "",
  "A frame at rest": "",
  "A non-inertial frame accelerates or rotates. In such frames, Newton's laws don't hold in their usual form — pseudo-forces must be introduced.": "",
  "What is a pseudo-force (fictitious force)?": "",
  "A real force that is very weak compared to other forces in the system, but still originates from a physical interaction between two real objects in contact": "",
  "A force that only acts on objects lighter than one kilogram, since heavier objects have too much inertia to be affected by fictitious force interactions": "",
  "A force that only appears in theoretical physics textbooks but never manifests during actual real-world experiments or practical engineering applications": "",
  "An apparent force that appears in a non-inertial reference frame to account for the frame's acceleration — it has no real physical source": "",
  "Pseudo-forces arise because the reference frame itself is accelerating. They have no agent (no third law partner) and disappear when viewed from an inertial frame.": "",
  "When you are in a car that accelerates forward, you feel pushed backward. What is this 'force'?": "",
  "Air pressure building up inside the car cabin as it accelerates forward, creating a backward-directed pressure gradient that pushes occupants toward the rear": "",
  "A real backward force transmitted from the engine through the car frame, pushing the passengers in the opposite direction of the vehicle's forward acceleration": "",
  "A pseudo-force — your body's inertia resists the forward acceleration, creating the sensation of being pushed backward in the car's non-inertial frame": "",
  "Gravity shifting direction temporarily during the acceleration event, tilting slightly backward relative to the car's floor and pulling passengers toward the rear": "",
  "In the car's (accelerating) frame, a pseudo-force pushes you backward. In an inertial frame view, your body simply maintains its velocity while the car accelerates forward beneath you.": "",
  "The centrifugal force is what type of force?": "",
  "The Newton's third law reaction partner to the centripetal force, acting on the same object but in the opposite radially outward direction from the center": "",
  "A fundamental force of nature alongside gravity and electromagnetism, classified as one of the four basic physical interactions governing all matter and energy": "",
  "A real physical contact force that pushes objects outward through direct molecular interaction between the spinning surface and the object placed upon it": "",
  "A pseudo-force — it appears in rotating reference frames, pointing outward from the rotation axis": "",
  "Centrifugal force is fictitious — it only appears when you analyze motion from a rotating frame. In an inertial frame, objects move in straight lines; no outward force exists.": "",
  "In a rotating reference frame, a ball rolling across a spinning platform curves to one side. What pseudo-force causes this?": "",
  "Centrifugal force": "",
  "Gravity": "",
  "Friction": "",
  "The Coriolis force": "",
  "The Coriolis force is a pseudo-force that deflects moving objects in rotating frames. It is perpendicular to the object's velocity in the rotating frame.": "",
  "Do pseudo-forces obey Newton's third law?": "",
  "Yes all forces without exception obey Newton's third law, including pseudo-forces, because the third law is a universal principle that applies in every reference frame": "",
  "Yes the reaction partner exists in the inertial reference frame, because every pseudo-force has a corresponding real reaction force acting on the accelerating frame itself": "",
  "Only in some special cases where the non-inertial frame has constant acceleration, because the third law applies partially during uniform non-inertial acceleration only": "",
  "No — pseudo-forces have no reaction pair because they are not real interactions between objects": "",
  "Pseudo-forces violate Newton's third law — there is no 'other object' providing the reaction force. This is a key way to identify them as fictitious.": "",
  "In an elevator accelerating downward at g, what apparent weight do you feel?": "",
  "Double your normal weight, because the downward acceleration adds to the gravitational pull and creates a stronger net force pressing you into the elevator floor": "",
  "Zero — you feel weightless because the pseudo-force in the elevator frame cancels gravity": "",
  "Half your normal weight, because the downward acceleration partially cancels the gravitational force, reducing the normal force to approximately half of your true weight": "",
  "Your normal weight unchanged, because the elevator's acceleration has no effect on the reading of a properly calibrated scale regardless of the direction of motion": "",
  "In the elevator's frame: F_pseudo = mg upward (opposing the downward acceleration). Net: mg (down) − mg (pseudo up) = 0. You feel weightless.": "",
  "On a spinning merry-go-round, which way does the centrifugal pseudo-force point?": "",
  "Downward": "",
  "Tangent to the circle": "",
  "Outward — away from the center of rotation": "",
  "Inward — toward the center": "",
  "Centrifugal force points radially outward in the rotating frame. It is the pseudo-force equivalent of the inertia that makes you feel pushed outward on spinning rides.": "",
  "Why do we call pseudo-forces 'fictitious'?": "",
  "Because they are very small in magnitude compared to real forces and therefore negligible in most practical calculations and engineering design applications": "",
  "Because they cannot be measured by any instrument or detected by any sensor, existing purely as conceptual tools that produce no observable physical effects": "",
  "Because they have no real physical origin — they are mathematical corrections needed to make Newton's laws work in non-inertial frames": "",
  "Because they only exist in theoretical models and never manifest in actual reality, having been disproven by modern experiments that show they do not occur": "",
  "Pseudo-forces are called fictitious because they don't arise from real interactions between objects. They are artifacts of using an accelerating reference frame.": "",
  "The Coriolis effect on Earth causes large-scale wind patterns to curve. In the Northern Hemisphere, moving air deflects to the:": "",
  "Right": "",
  "Upward": "",
  "Left": "",
  "Straight ahead": "",
  "In the Northern Hemisphere, the Coriolis effect deflects moving objects to the right of their direction of travel. This causes cyclones to spin counterclockwise.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a non-inertial reference frame?": "",
  "A frame that is attached to a very large massive object like a planet or star, since only large objects can serve as valid non-inertial reference frame anchors": "",
  "A frame inside which no experiments of any kind can be validly performed, because the frame's motion corrupts all measurements taken within its boundaries": "",
  "A frame that moves at perfectly constant velocity relative to all other frames, experiencing no acceleration and fully obeying Newton's laws in their standard form": "",
  "A reference frame that is accelerating, decelerating, or rotating, in which Newton's laws of motion do not hold in their standard form without introducing fictitious forces": "",
  "In a non-inertial frame, objects appear to accelerate without any apparent real force. To 'fix' Newton's second law in such frames, pseudo-forces are added.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a pseudo-force?": "",
  "A very weak but real force that originates from an actual physical interaction between two objects, having a definite third law partner and a clear physical source": "",
  "An apparent force introduced in a non-inertial reference frame to make Newton's second law valid — it equals −ma_frame where a_frame is the frame's acceleration": "",
  "Any force that proves difficult to measure accurately in a laboratory setting, regardless of whether it has a real physical source or obeys Newton's third law": "",
  "A force that acts exclusively on imaginary or hypothetical objects that do not physically exist, and therefore has no relevance to any real experimental situation": "",
  "Pseudo-force = −m × a_frame. It has no physical agent, no third law pair, and vanishes when viewed from an inertial frame.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes centrifugal force?": "",
  "A force that operates exclusively in outer space environments where there is no atmosphere, since centrifugal effects cannot occur in the presence of air molecules": "",
  "A real physical force that genuinely pushes objects outward during circular motion through direct contact, originating from the spinning surface beneath the object": "",
  "Exactly the same force as centripetal force described using a different name, since both terms refer to the identical center-directed inward force in every situation": "",
  "The pseudo-force that appears in a rotating reference frame, directed radially outward from the axis of rotation, equal to mω²r": "",
  "Centrifugal force (mω²r, outward) is the pseudo-force in a rotating frame. It is the reason you feel pushed against the car door in a turn — in the car's rotating frame, this pseudo-force acts outward.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the Coriolis force?": "",
  "A force that only exists at the equator of a rotating body and has zero magnitude at every other latitude, including the poles and all intermediate positions": "",
  "A pseudo-force in a rotating frame that acts perpendicular to the velocity of a moving object, deflecting its path — equal to −2m(ω × v) in the rotating frame": "",
  "The gravitational force acting on objects that are spinning about their own internal axis, which increases proportionally with the rate of the object's self-rotation": "",
  "A force that causes objects to rotate faster and faster over time by adding angular momentum through direct energy transfer from the rotating reference frame itself": "",
  "The Coriolis force deflects moving objects in rotating frames. On Earth, it affects weather patterns (cyclones), ocean currents, and long-range ballistics. F_Cor = −2m(ω × v).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the equivalence principle?": "",
  "Einstein's principle that locally, gravitational effects are indistinguishable from effects of acceleration — a person in an accelerating elevator cannot distinguish the 'force' from real gravity": "",
  "The principle that all pseudo-forces are always equal in magnitude to each other regardless of the reference frame, mass of the object, or acceleration involved": "",
  "The principle that mass always equals weight in every reference frame, making the two quantities perfectly interchangeable under all physical conditions and locations": "",
  "The principle that all reference frames are equivalent for all experiments, meaning every measurement yields identical results no matter which frame the observer uses": "",
  "The equivalence principle states that a uniform gravitational field is locally indistinguishable from uniform acceleration. This is the foundation of general relativity.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes apparent weight?": "",
  "Always exactly equal to the true gravitational weight mg regardless of any acceleration, since scales always display the correct gravitational force at all times": "",
  "The weight of an object measured on a different planet, which differs from the Earth value solely because of the different gravitational field strength at the surface": "",
  "The total mass of an object measured in kilograms, which is an intrinsic property of matter that does not change with location, acceleration, or reference frame": "",
  "The normal force experienced by a person or object, which can differ from true weight in an accelerating (non-inertial) reference frame": "",
  "Apparent weight = N (scale reading). In an elevator accelerating up: N = m(g + a) > mg. Accelerating down: N = m(g − a) < mg. Free fall: N = 0.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the Eötvös effect?": "",
  "The stretching and compressing of extended objects by tidal forces from a nearby gravitational source, also known as spaghettification in extreme gravitational fields": "",
  "The apparent change in gravitational acceleration experienced by objects moving east or west on a rotating planet, caused by the Coriolis force having a vertical component": "",
  "The bending of light rays as they pass through a strong gravitational field near a massive object, predicted by Einstein's general theory of relativity in 1915": "",
  "The slow wobble of Earth's rotational axis over a 26000-year cycle, caused by the gravitational torques exerted by the Sun and Moon on Earth's equatorial bulge": "",
  "Moving east on Earth increases your effective orbital speed, producing an outward Coriolis component that slightly reduces apparent gravity. Moving west has the opposite effect.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes frame-dependent quantities?": "",
  "Quantities that can only be measured by a single specific observer in one particular reference frame, and are completely inaccessible to all other observers": "",
  "Physical quantities whose measured values depend on the reference frame of the observer — such as velocity, kinetic energy, and momentum": "",
  "Quantities whose measured values remain exactly the same regardless of which reference frame the observer uses, such as mass, electric charge, and temperature": "",
  "Quantities that have no units of measurement and are expressed as pure dimensionless numbers, making them independent of any particular measurement system": "",
  "Many quantities are frame-dependent: velocity, KE, momentum. However, some quantities are frame-independent (invariant): mass, charge, spacetime interval (in relativity).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes tidal force in the context of non-inertial frames?": "",
  "The differential force arising because a gravitational field varies in strength and direction across an extended body, causing stretching along the direction toward the source": "",
  "The centrifugal force experienced by the Moon as it orbits the Earth, pushing it outward and balancing the gravitational attraction to maintain a stable orbit": "",
  "A pseudo-force that exists only in rotating reference frames and has no connection to gravitational fields, gradients, or variations in field strength across objects": "",
  "The force that ocean tides exert on a ship floating on the water surface, pushing the vessel up and down as the water level changes with the tidal cycle": "",
  "Tidal forces arise from gravitational gradients. Near Earth's center, gravity partially cancels, but the near and far sides experience different pulls, stretching the body radially.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the rotating frame pseudo-force equation?": "",
  "F_eff = F_real − mA − 2m(ω × v') − mω × (ω × r'), combining the translational pseudo-force, Coriolis force, and centrifugal force terms": "",
  "F = ma applied in a standard inertial reference frame, where no pseudo-forces are needed and Newton's second law works in its simplest and most familiar form": "",
  "F = negative k times x for springs undergoing simple harmonic oscillation, describing the restoring force that pulls a compressed or stretched spring back to equilibrium": "",
  "F = mv squared divided by r for circular motion, giving the centripetal force needed to keep an object moving along a circular path of constant radius at constant speed": "",
  "In a general non-inertial (rotating + translating) frame: F_eff = F_real + F_translational + F_Coriolis + F_centrifugal. This allows Newton's second law to be applied in the non-inertial frame.": "",
  "You stand on a scale in an elevator accelerating upward at 3 m/s². Your mass is 70 kg. What does the scale read? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "1400 N — the scale reads N = 2mg = 2 times 70 times 10 = 1400 N, because upward acceleration always doubles the apparent weight shown on the scale reading": "",
  "910 N — apparent weight = m(g + a) = 70 × 13 = 910 N": "",
  "490 N — the scale reads N = m(g minus a) = 70 times (10 minus 3) = 490 N, because the upward acceleration subtracts from gravity rather than adding to it": "",
  "700 N — the scale reads N = mg = 70 times 10 = 700 N, because the elevator's acceleration has no effect on the weight displayed by a properly calibrated scale": "",
  "Apparent weight = N = m(g + a) = 70(10 + 3) = 910 N. The upward acceleration adds to the gravitational effect, making you feel heavier.": "",
  "You are in a van that brakes suddenly. A ball on the dashboard rolls forward. Explain from both inertial and non-inertial perspectives.": "",
  "Only the inertial frame perspective is physically correct and valid, because non-inertial frame descriptions are inherently wrong and always give incorrect predictions": "",
  "Both frames observe the same thing: the ball is pushed forward by the braking force transmitted through the dashboard surface, which acts identically in both frames": "",
  "Inertial: The ball continues at its original velocity (inertia) while the van decelerates beneath it; Non-inertial: A pseudo-force pushes the ball forward in the decelerating van's frame": "",
  "The ball rolls forward due to gravity alone in both frames, because the braking event tilts the effective gravitational field forward inside the decelerating vehicle": "",
  "Inertial frame: ball maintains its velocity (Newton's first law); van slows. Non-inertial (van) frame: ball accelerates forward due to a pseudo-force F = −ma_van. Both descriptions are self-consistent.": "",
  "A plumb bob hangs in an accelerating train. The train accelerates forward at 5 m/s². At what angle does the bob hang from vertical? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "arctan(5/10) = arctan(0.5) ≈ 26.6° from vertical, angled backward": "",
  "5 degrees from vertical — using theta = a in degrees gives theta = 5 degrees backward, because the angle in degrees always equals the numerical acceleration value": "",
  "45 degrees from vertical — using theta = a divided by g times 90 gives 5/10 times 90 = 45 degrees, because the angle scales linearly up to a maximum of 90 degrees": "",
  "90 degrees from vertical — the plumb bob hangs horizontally whenever the train accelerates, because any forward acceleration causes the bob to point straight backward": "",
  "In the train's frame, pseudo-force = ma backward and gravity = mg downward. The bob aligns with the resultant: tanθ = a/g = 5/10 = 0.5 → θ ≈ 26.6° from vertical.": "",
  "On a rotating space station designed to simulate gravity, the 'floor' is the outer wall. If the station has radius 100 m and rotates to produce 1g of artificial gravity, what is the rotation rate?": "",
  "0.1 rad/s — using omega = g divided by r = 9.8/100 = 0.098 rounded to 0.1 rad/s, because the rotation rate equals gravity divided by the station radius directly": "",
  "1 RPM — using RPM = g times r = 9.8 times 100 / 1000 = 0.98 rounded to 1 RPM, because the rotation rate is found from the product of gravity and radius": "",
  "ω = √(g/r) = √(9.8/100) ≈ 0.313 rad/s, or about 3 RPM": "",
  "10 RPM — using RPM = g = 9.8 rounded to 10, because the required rotation rate in RPM always numerically equals the gravitational acceleration being simulated": "",
  "Centrifugal acceleration = ω²r = g → ω = √(g/r) = √(9.8/100) ≈ 0.313 rad/s = 0.313 × 60/(2π) ≈ 3 RPM.": "",
  "A person in a car feels pushed to the right when the car turns left. Explain this using pseudo-forces.": "",
  "A real physical force from the seat cushion pushes the person to the right through direct contact, since the seat material actively generates a sideways pushing force": "",
  "The car door pushes the person inward toward the center of the turn, because the door's contact force acts centripetally on the passenger during every turning maneuver": "",
  "In the car's non-inertial (turning) frame, a centrifugal pseudo-force pushes the person outward (to the right) — in an inertial frame, the person's body simply continues straight while the car turns left": "",
  "Gravity shifts its direction during turns to point sideways instead of downward, temporarily pulling the person to the right until the car completes its left turn": "",
  "From inside the turning car (non-inertial frame): a centrifugal pseudo-force acts outward (rightward). From outside (inertial frame): the person's inertia carries them straight while the car curves left.": "",
  "The Coriolis effect deflects a ball thrown northward on a rotating turntable (counterclockwise as seen from above). Which way does the ball deflect?": "",
  "To the right (east) — in a counterclockwise rotating frame, the Coriolis force deflects motion to the right": "",
  "The ball does not deflect at all in any direction, because the Coriolis force is too small to produce any observable effect on objects moving on a turntable surface": "",
  "To the left or west — in a counterclockwise rotating frame the Coriolis force deflects all northward-moving objects to the left of their initial direction of travel": "",
  "Straight up off the surface of the turntable, because the Coriolis force acts perpendicular to both the velocity and the rotation axis in the vertical direction only": "",
  "For counterclockwise rotation, F_Cor = −2m(ω × v) deflects objects to the right of their velocity direction. This is analogous to the Northern Hemisphere's Coriolis effect.": "",
  "An astronaut in a freely falling spacecraft releases a ball. The ball appears to float motionless beside her. Explain using pseudo-forces.": "",
  "The ball is held in place by the air pressure inside the sealed spacecraft cabin, which creates an equilibrium zone that prevents any object from drifting in any direction": "",
  "In the spacecraft's non-inertial frame (free-fall), the gravitational pseudo-force exactly cancels real gravity, making the effective gravity zero — everything inside appears weightless": "",
  "There is no gravity present in outer space at the spacecraft's altitude, so the ball simply has no force acting on it and naturally remains stationary beside the astronaut": "",
  "The ball has no mass while inside the spacecraft because objects lose their mass in microgravity environments, making them immune to all forces including gravity": "",
  "In the free-falling frame, the pseudo-force is mg upward, exactly canceling the real gravitational force mg downward. The net effective force is zero, producing apparent weightlessness.": "",
  "Earth rotates. At the equator, how does this affect your apparent weight compared to the poles?": "",
  "There is no difference between the equator and poles, because Earth's rotation has no measurable effect on the apparent weight of objects at any latitude on the surface": "",
  "Apparent weight drops to exactly zero at the equator because the centrifugal pseudo-force completely cancels gravity, making all objects weightless at equatorial latitudes": "",
  "Your apparent weight is slightly less at the equator because the centrifugal pseudo-force (pointing outward) partially opposes gravity — the effect is about 0.3%": "",
  "Apparent weight is actually greater at the equator than at the poles, because the centrifugal pseudo-force adds to gravity rather than opposing it at lower latitudes": "",
  "At the equator, centrifugal acceleration = ω²R ≈ 0.034 m/s² outward. This reduces apparent g by about 0.3%. At the poles, there is no centrifugal effect (r = 0).": "",
  "A helicopter drops supplies to a ship. If the ship is at latitude 60°N and the supplies fall for 10 seconds, roughly which direction do they deflect due to the Coriolis effect?": "",
  "The supplies deflect to the east — falling objects in the Northern Hemisphere are deflected eastward by the Coriolis effect because they move from a region of lower to higher angular velocity": "",
  "The supplies deflect to the north, because the Coriolis force always pushes falling objects toward the nearest geographic pole in both hemispheres of the rotating Earth": "",
  "There is no measurable deflection of the falling supplies, because the Coriolis effect only acts on objects moving horizontally and has zero effect on vertically falling items": "",
  "The supplies deflect to the west, because falling objects in the Northern Hemisphere always drift westward due to the Coriolis force acting opposite to Earth's rotation": "",
  "A falling object at 60°N moves from a higher altitude (slower Earth rotation speed) to a lower altitude (faster rotation at the ground). In the Earth's frame, this appears as an eastward deflection.": "",
  "A double-decker bus rounds a curve. Passengers on the upper deck feel more 'pushed outward' than those on the lower deck. Why?": "",
  "Gravity is stronger at greater heights above the road surface, pulling upper-deck passengers outward with more force during the turn than passengers closer to the ground": "",
  "The upper deck is farther from the road surface and closer to the center of the curve doesn't explain it. Actually, passengers on the upper deck are at a greater height, and the bus tilts slightly, creating a larger effective pseudo-force displacement. More precisely, at greater height the tangential speed is slightly higher during body sway, amplifying the sensation": "",
  "The upper deck has less friction between the seats and passengers, allowing passengers to slide more easily and therefore feel a stronger sensation of being pushed outward": "",
  "The upper deck passengers experience greater centrifugal pseudo-force because they are farther from the center of the curve, since F = m times omega squared times r increases with larger r and greater height amplifies the tipping": "",
  "At the upper deck, passengers are farther from the center of the curve (larger effective radius), so the centrifugal pseudo-force (mω²r) is slightly larger. Additionally, the greater height amplifies the tipping sensation.": ""
}